DATE: 2026-04-02T11:00:00Z
DECISION_ID: D-0321
CATEGORY: security | fix | rbac
CONTEXT: V13-4D — Data scoping audit across all service provider portals + cross-portal data leakage check.
  Audited 6 portals (cleaning, security, contractor, supplier, PMC, developer) and 5 high-value BM API routes.
OPTIONS_CONSIDERED:
  1. Cleaning portal: /api/cleaning/areas, checklists, dashboard, operations, staff — all properly use
     getCleaningOrgBuildingIds(orgId) to scope queries. ISSUE: /api/cleaning/logs POST accepted any
     building_id from formData without verifying the org is assigned to that building. A cleaner could
     submit logs to arbitrary buildings.
  2. Security portal: All 6 routes (attendance, dashboard, guards, incidents, operations, shifts) — all
     properly use getSecurityOrgBuildingIds(orgId). /api/security/patrol is a worker-facing POST that
     resolves buildingId from staff assignment — no org-level scoping needed (workers submit their own
     location data). No issues.
  3. Contractor portal: All 9 routes (billing, dashboard-extras, invoices, jobs, orgs, schedule, staff,
     tenders, visits) — all properly scoped via getContractorOrgForUser + getOrgBuildingIds. /api/contractor/stores
     lists all approved stores (intentional marketplace). No issues.
  4. Supplier portal: credit, invoices, orders, settings — all filtered by supplier.id via getSupplierForUser.
     /api/supplier/tenders shows all open/quoting tenders (no supplier→building assignment table exists, so
     this is architecturally correct — suppliers browse the marketplace). No issues.
  5. PMC portal: All 5 routes (branding, buildings, dashboard, reports, settings, staff) — all properly resolve
     PMC org via building_org_assignments and scope to assigned buildings only. No issues.
  6. Developer portal: All 8 routes (contractors, dashboard, defects, developments, dlp-report, handover,
     legal, tenders) — all scope via getDeveloperOrgForUser + developments.developer_org_id. ISSUE:
     /api/developer/floor-plans (GET/POST/DELETE) verified the user has a developer org but did not verify
     the dev_building_id belongs to that org's developments — an IDOR vulnerability.
  7. BM API role guards: /api/bm/collection uses requirePermission (role-checked). /api/bm/staff uses
     requirePermission. /api/bm/residents POST/PATCH use requirePermission. ISSUE: /api/bm/dashboard GET,
     /api/bm/residents GET, and /api/bm/settings GET only checked session.buildingId — a committee member
     (who has buildingId) could call these endpoints and access BM data.
DECISION:
  FIX 1 — /api/cleaning/logs POST: Added org lookup (getCleaningOrgForUser) + building assignment
  validation (getCleaningOrgBuildingIds) before inserting the log. Returns 403 if building not assigned.
  FIX 2 — /api/bm/dashboard GET: Added BM_ROLES guard ['bm','staff','superadmin'] after buildingId check.
  FIX 3 — /api/bm/residents GET: Added BM_ROLES guard ['bm','staff','superadmin'] after buildingId check.
  FIX 4 — /api/bm/settings GET: Added BM_ROLES guard ['bm','staff','superadmin'] after buildingId check.
  FIX 5 — /api/developer/floor-plans (GET/POST/DELETE): Replaced simple verifyDevAccess() with
  verifyDevBuildingAccess() that queries dev_buildings.development_id → developments.developer_org_id to
  confirm ownership before serving/mutating floor plan data.
PORTALS WITH NO ISSUES FOUND: security, contractor, supplier, PMC.
MODIFIED: app/api/cleaning/logs/route.ts, app/api/bm/dashboard/route.ts, app/api/bm/residents/route.ts,
