DATE: 2026-04-04T00:00:00Z
DECISION: D-0339 — attendance_logs user_id column + clock-in flicker loop fix
CONTEXT: Face clock-in matched at 82.1% but attendance recording failed with "Could not find the 'user_id' column of 'attendance_logs' in the schema cache". The clock API already had user_id logic (line 171: if (user_id) insertData.user_id = user_id) but the DB column was missing. Compound issue: contractor_staff_id was NOT NULL so building-staff inserts (no contractor_staff) also failed. After the error, setView('scanner') re-mounted the scanner → face re-detected → clock attempted again → infinite loop.
SOLUTION:
  1. Migration 057a: ALTER TABLE attendance_logs ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS user_id UUID REFERENCES users(id) + index.
  2. Migration 057b: ALTER TABLE attendance_logs ALTER COLUMN contractor_staff_id DROP NOT NULL — allows building staff (no contractor_staff record) to clock in.
  3. clock/page.tsx: ViewState gets 'clock_error' state. On attendance recording failure: setView('clock_error') instead of setView('scanner'). clock_error view shows user-friendly "Clock-in failed" message (not raw Supabase error) + "Try Again" button that explicitly resets to scanner. This hard-stops the flicker loop.
  4. Removed floating error banner (was showing raw Supabase error text to users). Errors now shown only in clock_error view.
TRADE-OFFS: Either contractor_staff_id OR user_id should be set per row — no DB constraint enforces this (would require a CHECK constraint). Acceptable for now since clock API always sets one or the other.
DECIDED_BY: human + claude
TASK_REF: Hotfix — attendance recording + flicker loop
