DATE: 2026-04-04T00:00:00Z
DECISION_ID: D-0345
CATEGORY: architecture
CONTEXT: Attendance reads were scattered between PostgREST (.from('attendance_logs').select()) and Postgres RPCs. PostgREST queries on attendance_logs caused schema cache errors (columns not visible due to recent migrations) and produced incorrect results due to JS-side date math in UTC. The attendance check API, history API, and home page card all had inconsistent query patterns.
OPTIONS_CONSIDERED:
  1. Fix each PostgREST query individually — rejected (patchwork, same root cause recurs)
  2. Route ALL attendance reads through Postgres RPCs — selected (Postgres computes MYT boundaries, eliminates schema cache issues)
DECISION: All attendance reads use Postgres RPCs exclusively. Zero PostgREST .from('attendance_logs') queries remain in the codebase. Six RPCs handle all attendance data access:
  - get_attendance_today(p_building_id, p_user_id) → today's sessions with status + summary
  - get_attendance_history(p_building_id, p_user_id, p_limit) → paginated history grouped by date
  - find_open_attendance(p_building_id, p_user_id) → open session (clock_out_at IS NULL) for clock-out
  - count_today_sessions(p_building_id, p_user_id) → integer count of sessions today
  - get_attendance_today_by_staff(p_building_id, p_contractor_staff_id) → same as get_attendance_today for contractor staff
  - get_attendance_history_by_staff(p_building_id, p_contractor_staff_id, p_limit) → same as get_attendance_history for contractor staff
  All RPCs compute MYT date boundaries in Postgres using AT TIME ZONE 'Asia/Kuala_Lumpur'. No JS date math for attendance anywhere.
DECIDED_BY: human + claude
TASK_REF: Replace ALL PostgREST attendance reads with Postgres RPCs

