DATE: 2026-04-05T10:00:00Z
DECISION_ID: D-0350
CATEGORY: architecture
CONTEXT: Attendance status check API (/api/attendance/check) returns stale data — home page (/app) shows "No session yet" and clock page (/app/clock) shows "Clock in" even when user has active session. RPCs return correct data when tested directly via SQL. History API (/api/attendance/history) works correctly. Root cause: Next.js 14 patches global fetch() to add Data Cache behaviour. The supabaseAdmin client used the default fetch without cache opt-out, so internal PostgREST HTTP requests made by the Supabase JS client could be served from Next.js Data Cache. Additionally, the check route responses lacked explicit Cache-Control headers, leaving browser/CDN caching to heuristic defaults.
OPTIONS_CONSIDERED:
  1. Add cache: 'no-store' only to the check route via fetchCache segment config — rejected (doesn't fix other routes that may hit same issue)
  2. Fix supabaseAdmin client globally + add Cache-Control headers + fetchCache on check route — selected (comprehensive, follows Supabase Next.js best practice)
DECISION: Three-layer cache-busting fix:
  (1) lib/supabase/admin.ts — added global.fetch config with cache:'no-store' to the createClient call, following Supabase's official Next.js recommendation. This ensures ALL Supabase PostgREST requests bypass Next.js Data Cache across the entire app.
  (2) app/api/attendance/check/route.ts — added fetchCache='force-no-store' segment config as belt-and-suspenders for this critical route. Added explicit Cache-Control:'no-store, no-cache, must-revalidate' headers to ALL response paths (400, 500, not_started, clocked_in, clocked_out).
  (3) PostgREST schema cache reloaded via NOTIFY pgrst, 'reload schema' to ensure function signatures are current.
  Verification: 0 TypeScript errors. RPC get_attendance_today returns Arun's active session (clock_out_at=null). All core attendance reads use RPCs with named params.
DECIDED_BY: claude_code
TASK_REF: Fix attendance status stale — home page and clock page not detecting active session

